<TITLE> Stocks maintain upward curve on banks </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Apr 13 (bdnews24.com)Markets closed higher for the second straight day Monday, driven mainly by banks and non-bank financial institutions. Banks, accounting for more than 50 percent of the market capitalisation, continued to rise from the previous day and edged more than six percent on average, with some gaining over 10 percent. Trust Bank jumped 17.29 percent while Uttara Bank and AB Bank leaped 11.37 percent and 10.42 percent respectively. Market operators said the rise in banks might be the outcome of their high operating profits. "[Banks] gained by large margins probably on the news on the impressive gains in their operating profits," DSE senior vice president Saiful Islam said. Mutual funds and insurers emerged from the losing streak but power, energy and pharmaceutical shares continued to slide. Turnover on the bourses registered a slight decline from the previous day while trading volume fell significantly. Dhaka Stock Exchange The country's premier stock exchange saw 22,590,071 shares worth Tk 3.89 billion changing hands, edging down from Tk 3.90 billion the previous day. DSE's benchmark general index maintained an upward curve across Monday's trading session. It gained 29.60 points or 1.21 percent and closed on 2467.39. The DSI or all share price index ended on 2052.08, rising 23.20 points or 1.14 percent. The blue-chip DSE-20 went up 26.02 points or 1.36 percent to finish on 1933.23. Gainers beat losers 125 to 118 while five issues held steady. Beximco remained at the top of the board with a turnover of Tk 303.297 million. It fell 3.19 percent to Tk 245.40 following the previous day's gains. Summit Power followed, with turnover of Tk 208.614 million, to end 1.66 percent lower on Tk 1153.50. S Alam Cold Rolled Steels had shares worth Tk 187.637 million traded and slumped 7.50 percent to end on Tk 665.25. AB Bank ended on Tk 617, surging 10.42 percent. It saw shares worth Tk 175.687 million changing hands. Uttara Bank shot up 11.37 percent to Tk 1764.75 with a turnover of Tk 168.014 million. The other scrips on the turnover board Shinepukur Ceramics, Titas Gas, Beximco Pharmaceuticals, Bangladesh Online and Powergrid Company of Bangladeshalso witnessed losses. Chittagong Stock Exchange Turnover on the port city's bourse reached Tk 549.499 million from trading of 5,064,046 sharesslightly lower than Sunday's Tk 564.389 million. Banks, non-bank financial institutions and cement shares drove the indices to finish upbeat. The CSCX or selective categories index rose 70.86 points or 1.40 percent to close at 5112.31. The CASPI or all share price index ended on 7893.18, up by 95.70 points or 1.22 percent. The CSE-30 blue-chip shot up 185.81 points or 3.08 percent to finish at 6203.17. Of the traded issues, 87 declined, 78 advanced with five scrips unchanged. AIMS First Mutual Fund remained the turnover leader with transactions of Tk 1.37 million, followed by Bextex Ltd, Grameen Mutual Fund One: Scheme 2, Prime Finance First Mutual Fund and Shinepukur Ceramics.
